<p><b>Johann Eduard Hari</b> (born 21 January 1979) is a British writer and journalist who has written regular columns for <i><a href="/wiki/The_Independent" title="The Independent">The Independent</a></i> (London) and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Huffington_Post" title="The Huffington Post">The Huffington Post</a></i> and made contributions to several other publications. In 2011, he was suspended from <i>The Independent</i> following multiple charges of plagiarism and was separately accused of making malicious edits of several of his critics' <a href="/wiki/Wikipedia" title="Wikipedia">Wikipedia</a> pages under a <a href="/wiki/Sockpuppet_(Internet)" title="Sockpuppet (Internet)">pseudonym</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> an allegation he later admitted to.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> The exposed plagiarism led to his being forced to return his 2008 <a href="/wiki/Orwell_Prize" title="Orwell Prize">Orwell Prize</a><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> and later was a contributing factor in his leaving <i>The Independent</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
<p></p>
